ch.p:
I don’t care to have anything to do with Bezúkhova and don’t advise you to;
                    however, if you’ve promised—go. It will divert your thoughts, she added,
                addressing Natásha.

Balagá was a fair-haired, short, and snub-nosed peasant of about twenty-seven;
                red-faced, with a particularly red thick neck, glittering little eyes, and a small
                beard. He wore a fine, dark-blue, silk-lined cloth coat over a sheepskin.
